ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.
M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: Latency to first fear response:(Stranger Approach)
Notes: Interval; in seconds; from the time when the stranger knocks on the door to the first definite fear response.

ElementDescription: Peak Intensity of vocal distress: Average
Peak Intensity of activity decrease: Greets;watches C(Stranger Approach)
Notes:
0 = No sign of decreased activity; 1 = Low decreased activity. For example; C fidgets before stranger approaches
and abruptly stands very still as stranger nears; 2 = Medium decreased activity. Bodily tensing: visible tensing of the muscles such as tightening and raising of shoulders; associated with decreased activity. For example; hands formed in to tight wrists or raising shoulders to sigh/control breathing; 3 = High bodily fear. Freezing (tensing entire body with very little motion)
